The Minister for Foreign Affairs of North Korea told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of sanctions was aggravating distrust over the United States and that there was no way for the country unilaterally to dispense with its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as the interruption of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear testing centre and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see any corresponding responses from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the US there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there will be no way for us to proceed to our disarmament first."
Although Ri has recycled well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, within which North Korea would be rewarded as it took graduate steps, its statements appear to be significant to the extent that they do not fully reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between a US President in exercise and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim undertook to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States claims that Pyongyang has first to abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "unnuclearization first" and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, opposing the "declaration of the end of the war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is aggravating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been mentioned by the US leader in the United Nations at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the interested party on this issue were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse".
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that guiding the rockets of North Korea towards the U.S. territory was inevitable after "Mr. President Mau" Trump called Kim the "man of rockets" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, filled Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but claimed that much was still to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until the denuclearization of North Korea.
