Harvard students attend courses that teach them to rest enough
A new course at Harvard University this year put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the macho culture of studying in "direct" impregnated with caffeine.
One teacher concluded that students from this university at the top of the world ranking often did not have the slightest idea about the most basic concepts about the care they should have with themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, who believes he is the first of his kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course arose after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you just saying this to me in the last year of the course?"
The young woman said that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first given this year, explains the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university health services, said that the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dorm where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, shoes and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to pick up to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know you won't change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as we all have the right to know the health effects of the option to smoke," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in "making straight" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
To ensure that we sleep enough and with quality should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, because deprivation of sleep puts the brain in a hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a course for the entire campus, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar study program before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students apply an alarm to go to bed as well as to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to problems in falling asleep.
