Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
Key piece of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become a central element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" in which the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans participated:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like a uranium.
When we put these headphones, we can even hear the effects of atoms released by radioactivity on minerals."
Evans: "Look, now you're really tripping!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention you gave the name still lasts.
New cancer vaccine teaches the immune system to "see" harmful cells
A new cancer vaccine teaches the immune system to "see" harmful cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and its modification in the laboratory
These cells, which can "see" a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a series of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, who teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her cancer in the ovaries disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their modification in the laboratory to "see" a protein common to many cancers, designated by HER2. These cells are then reinjected into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancer", including breast, ovary, lungs and also colorectals, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach to removing immune cells from patients and "teaching them" to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
