What is the Global Citizen Festival? Have you done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, the city of New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual musical event with an extremely impressive list of stars that will perform on an equally impressive mission: to eradicate poverty in the world.
In its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will host tens of thousands of people at the Grand Relvado do Central Park, not only to witness the actions of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to strengthen awareness of the true objective of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a defense group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket for the event (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) spectators had to perform a series of tasks, or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an e-mail to a world leader, a phone call or any other significant forms that contribute to increasing awareness of the goal of ending poverty.
However, what has been the degree of success of Global Citizen in these 12 years in achieving its goal?
The idea of rewarding people with a free concert is a genuine way to persuade them to demand action, or this is just another case of "clickivism" - do we think it makes any difference to sign an online petition or send a tweet?
Global Citizen states that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million "actions" of its supporters who have exerted pressure to achieve a number of different objectives.
These actions, according to the organization, contributed to the announcement by world leaders of commitments and policies valued at more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group quoted 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, with at least $10 billion referring to the same being already disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that the funds obtained have so far had a direct impact on almost 649 million people scattered around the world.
Some of the main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a partnership based in the United Kingdom bringing together investors and implementers committed to "help children achieve their full potential", which promised to give Rwanda $35 million to help end undernutrition in the country. This after receiving more than 4700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like all of us, we can make the social injustice of undernutrition a footnote to History," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, to a crowd in a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group further stated that, after more than 5000 pressure actions on the United Kingdom to improve nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced that it would finance a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will cover 5 million women and children, with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequent questions on the site, "What makes you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen answers: "It was a long and tortuous way - sometimes we fall and fail.
But, like the great movements for civil and anti-apartheid rights that preceded us, because we are more powerful together.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are among the artists who will be performing this year's event in New York, presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
