The first salvation of the trade war between the United States and China was shocking, and although the end of the conflict is not in sight, in the perspective of the experts, the removal of the two countries can be beneficial for Beijing in the long term.
Donald Trump, U.S. President, fired the first notice at the beginning of the year by charging important Chinese imports including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
This week was the stage of a significant worsening of the situation with the new taxes to affect goods worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), charging in reality half of all goods sent by China to the US.
Beijing has always retaliated in the same currency, recently raising the rates from 5 to 10 percent for US goods worth $60 billion.
China has committed itself to following the steps of the U.S. and it is unlikely that the second largest economy in the world will be wavering in the near future.
Making Washington back would mean yielding to demands, but showing a public subservience to the U.S. would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing makes good use of its triumphs, the pressures imposed by the US trade war can sustain China positively in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"In reality, the fact that an early political decision in Washington or Beijing can result in an economic crisis in both countries is far more dangerous than observers could ever have anticipated," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher dedicated to the study of Asia at the Center for New American Security, a reflection group.
Minister for Foreign Affairs states that Syria is prepared for the return of refugees
Syria claims to be prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding a country devastated by more than seven long years of war.
In his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the conditions of the country are improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to progress in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
There are now all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that have left because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people who have remained in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would gladly receive aid for the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he pointed out that he would not accept conditional assistance or aid from the countries that sponsored the revolt.
